==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tyrannize
<hw>Tyr"an*nize</hw> <pr>(t⟦icr⟧r"⟦ait⟧n*n⟦imac⟧z)</pr>, <pos>v.
i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Tyrannized</conjf>
<pr>(t⟦icr⟧r"⟦ait⟧n*n⟦imac⟧zd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tyrannizing</conjf>
<pr>(t⟦icr⟧r"⟦ait⟧n*n⟦imac⟧`z⟦icr⟧ng)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>tyranniser</ets>, Gr. <grk>tyranni`zein</grk> to take the part of
tyrants.]</ety> <def>To act the tyrant; to exercise arbitrary power; to
rule with unjust and oppressive severity; to exercise power over others
not permitted by law or required by justice, or with a severity not
necessary to the ends of justice and government; <as>as, a prince will
often <ex>tyrannize</ex> over his subjects; masters sometimes
<ex>tyrannize</ex> over their servants or apprentices</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tyrannize</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tyrannize
<hw>Tyr"an*nize</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To subject to arbitrary,
oppressive, or tyrannical treatment; to oppress.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tyrannous</ent>⟦br⟧
